<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>How Kemper Shareholders Evaluate
Performance</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../gifs/white_bk.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="../gifs/headers/date_hd.gif"
ALT="Kemper.com">
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT
SRC="../gifs/headers/search_spacer_hd.gif">
<A HREF="../search.html"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 SRC="../gifs/headers/search_hd.gif" ALT="Search"></A>

<A HREF="understand_fundsmenu.html">
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 SRC="gifs/headers/understand_gry_hd.gif" 
ALT="Understanding Mutual Funds"></A>

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<BR>
<NOBR>
<A HREF="../prospectus.html"><IMG SRC="../gifs/link_wht_prospectuses.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 ALT="Prospectuses And Important Information"></A>
<A HREF="../learn/contact_learn.html"><IMG SRC="../gifs/link_wht_contactkemper.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="Contact Kemper"></A>
<A HREF="../sitemap.html"><IMG SRC="../gifs/link_wht_sitemap.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="Site Map"></A>
</NOBR>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<BR>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="gifs/understand_sidebar.gif">

<DL><DT>

<IMG SRC="gifs/evaluate_perform_head.gif"
ALT="How Kemper Shareholders
Evaluate Performance">
<BR>

<IMG SRC="gifs/evaluate_perform_subhead.gif"
ALT="What's important to
you about mutual fund performance?">
<BR>

(Continued)
<BR><BR>

<!-- question 3 -->

<IMG SRC="gifs/eval_perf_question3.gif" ALT="3"
CLEAR=RIGHT>
No mutual fund can guarantee future results.
Which of the following
would you consider the most encouraging about
your fund?
<BR><BR>

<IMG SRC="gifs/eval_perf5_chart.gif"
ALT="Chart">
<BR>

<BR><BR>

<IMG SRC="gifs/eval_perf6_chart.gif"
ALT="Chart">
<BR>

<BR><BR>

<!-- question 4 -->

<IMG SRC="gifs/eval_perf_question4.gif" ALT="4"
CLEAR=RIGHT>
Which of the following events would you consider
the least
encouraging?
<BR><BR>

<IMG SRC="gifs/eval_perf7_chart.gif"
ALT="Chart">
<BR>

<BR><BR>

<IMG SRC="gifs/eval_perf8_chart.gif"
ALT="Chart">
<BR><BR>

A change in total return, considered to be the
best measure of fund
performance, could occur as a result of a change
in a dividend paid, a
change in net asset value or a combination of
both. 
<BR><BR>

Income fund shareholders may be more sensitive to
changes in dividends
because of their relative higher reliance on
dividend income. In
addition, income funds often pay as frequently as
once a month. 
<BR><BR>

Dividends paid by an equity fund include
distributions of the dividends
paid by stocks owned by the portfolio and any
profits earned when
individual stocks are sold. Any gains are
distributed at least annually,
and it is reasonable to expect some variation in
the dividend payment
from period to period.
<BR><BR>

Information on the fund's performance compared to
funds with similar
investment objectives can provide an insight that
absolute return
numbers cannot. No investor is pleased with
negative returns, for
example, but there will always be economic
periods that are hostile to
investors. 
<BR><BR>


<I>This article was excerpted from the
Fall/Winter 1995 issue of </I>Kemper
Reports, <I>Kemper's quarterly shareholder
magazine.</I>

<BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=1>&copy; Copyright Kemper Distributors, Inc. 1996 - All rights reserved.</FONT SIZE=1>

</DL>
