<P>
<br>
<A NAME="Announce">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="http://www.privacy.org/ipc/"><img width=500
 src="http://www.privacy.org/ipc/logo/swash.gif"
ALT="________________________________________________"><BR><img 
 src="http://www.privacy.org/ipc/logo/gk7.gif" ALT="Back to IPC Homepage"></A>
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><FONT SIZE=6>L</FONT>ATEST <FONT SIZE=6>N</FONT>EWS </FONT><FONT SIZE=4></A>

<UL>

<li>Senator Conrad Burns announced at the 1997 RSA Data Security Conference that he plans to reintroduce his PRO-CODE legislation. Rep. Goodlatte also announced that he plans to introduce his companion legislation in the House. <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.rsa.com/rsa_conf_audio.html">RealAudio</A> of day one of the conference.<P>

<li>The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia has remanded  the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.qualcomm.com/people/pkarn/export">Karn v. State Dept.</A> case back to the U.S. District Court in light of the new regulations.<P>

<li>The White House released <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.privacy.org/ipc/crypto_regs_1296.html">new regulations</A> on December 30 on the export of cryptography. Jurisdiction for controls has been moved from State to commerce but the sma econtrols apply. Key escrow products will receive "favorable consideration". Products containing DES may be exported for 2 years but only if the company produces a "satisfactory business and marketing plan that explains in detail the steps the applicant will take during the two years transitiion period to develop, produce, and/or market encryption items and services with recoverable features." The new regulations go into effect December 30. Comments can be sent until Feb. 13, 1997.  Business groups led by the Business Software Alliance earlier described the regulations as "moving in the wrong direction."<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.news.com/News/Item/0,4,6135,00.html">C|net story</A> on the opposition. The White House released the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.epic.org/crypto/export_controls/executive_order_11_15_96.html">executive order</A> on encryption exports on November 18.<P>
<P>

<LI> The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development in Paris <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.oecd.org/news_and_events/release/nw96119a.htm">announced</A> that they had completed their Guidelines for Cryptography Policy. The Guidelines emphasize "voluntary, market-driven development" of cryptography and include a strong principle in support of privacy protection. Key escrow has been downplayed.<P>

<li>US District Court Judge Patel ruled in the <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.eff.org/pub/Privacy/ITAR_export/Bernstein_case/Legal/">Bernstein v. US case</A> on December 18 that current restrictions on exports of cryptography violate the First Amendment.<P>

<LI> Many of the world's leading human and cyber rights organizations signed a <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.gilc.org/gilc/resolution.html">resolution</A> supporting unresticted use of cryptography. The groups also sponsored a <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.epic.org/events/crypto_paris/">conference</A> to educate the OECD on the public and technical views on cryptography policy.<P>

</UL>
